== Childhood

#align(right)[Aug 31, 2025 $sun$]

#figure(
  image("img/mantis.jpg"),
)

The gray praying mantis attempting to escape its plastic prison was the first thing Monkey, my son, spotted when we arrived at the new playground in the neighborhood. I had a mantis back when I was not much older than Monkey, if my memory serves. It was green and quite large, which bit off the head of a grasshopper, captivating me as it continued to devour the corpse. But there's little time for my childhood flashbacks: Monkey dashes off towards the little mound full of handholds and tunnels, crying out in glee.

And so it went—mound-climbing, slide-riding, tunnel-crawling—it was clear that Monkey was enjoying himself, keeping busy with various explorations, running back and forth, and completely ignoring me. I had to content myself with occasionally shouting "be careful" and offering water when he was in the mood. And it was just right—who was I to interfere with his adventures? Perhaps in his mind, he had a world to save, a kingdom to conquer.

Eventually, he settled down, probably out of fatigue, to digging in the sand with some seriousness, underneath a long ramp. After a while, when he tried to stand up, he forgot about the ramp and bumped his head against the edge of it. I heard a clear thump, but he didn't mind, didn't even complain. That's how focused his mind is.

Yes, that focus of attention, the determination not to be disturbed, comes perhaps more easily to a child than to a grown-up like myself, whose mind is troubled by many worries and agitations. It is certainly one of the things I miss dearly about childhood.


