To my knowledge, the Ferris wheel in Longtan Park has stood motionless for some 30 years. Back then the park was known as the Beijing Amusement Park, a distinctive, fond place in the childhood memories of my generation. It was an indisputable royal treatment to have a go in the giant wheel, which already enjoyed landmark status in all of Beijing.

Not many people known this, but rumor had it that one day, one carriage on the Wheel caught fire and some students were burnt to their death. A terrifying tragedy. The amusement park had since shut down, becoming quite ruined for many years, a dilapidated, gloomy yet mysterious place in my memory, until only a couple of years ago when Longtan reopened as a normal park. The Wheel however has never been turned on again. A giant statue of sorts. A landmark. Its memory lost on the many happy faces wondering at its looming presence.





== Approaching Ancient Text

My approach to these texts is to treat them like an archaeological puzzle: I have arrived at an open field full of fossilized bones, as the texts are quite intimidating at first glance. The individual words I can recognize, yes, but the meaning of the sentences eludes understanding.

This is no doubt due to the texts' age—they were written hundreds of years ago in a scholarly style that is now almost extinct. But herein lies the intrigue: can I piece together these scattered relics and reconstruct the beast?

So, I repeatedly scan the text, trying to connect the dots. Each time, I gain a little more insight—a process involving much guesswork and reading between the lines—until at last the Tyrannosaurus rex emerges with a roar, and every word's purpose crystallized.

Ultimately, the messages of these texts are not so interesting; they are mostly personal opinions and empty philosophizing, reiterations of familiar ideas that have fallen out of fashion. But I can't honestly complain, for the chase is better than the catch :)


